In this speech delivered at the Philadelphia Convention Center, President Joe Biden addresses the AFL-CIO and expresses his gratitude for the support of labor unions throughout his career. He pays tribute to the late Rich Trumka, former president of the AFL-CIO, and emphasizes his commitment to being the "most pro-union President in history." Biden discusses his administration's accomplishments, including the American Rescue Plan and the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law, and highlights his plans to bring down gas and food prices, lower prescription drug costs, and invest in clean energy. He calls for corporations and the wealthy to pay their fair share in taxes and criticizes the Republican Party's opposition to his proposals. Biden concludes by urging unions to continue fighting for working families and building a better America.